as at Austin alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Texas]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013Vietnam War activists]]\n[[Category:People from Lakeville, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:People from Taylor, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Temple, Texas]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Czech descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Moravian-German descent]]\n", "name_user": "Jeremy68", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rip_Torn"}
{"title_page": "Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142", "text_new": "{{short description|Polish Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142\n| image = Barbara Niewiedzial - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Niewiedzia\u0142 at the 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships in Lyon.\n| nationality =Polish\n| sport = [[track and field]]\n| event  = [[400m]]<br/>[[800m]]<br/>[[1500m]]\n| club = MGOKSiR Korfantow\n| collegeteam = \n| coach = Mariusz Zabinski (club)<br/>Zbigniew Lewkowicz (national)\n| birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1981|09|01|df=y}}\n| disability_class = [[T20 (classification)|T20]]\n| disability= Intellectual impairment\n| birth_place = [[Nysa, Poland]]\n| residence = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| weight = \n|website = \n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|3|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|5|1|0\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|3|0|0\n}}\n{{MedalSport | [[Paralympic athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry|{{POL}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Paralympics|800 metres \u2013 T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T20|1500 metres \u2013 T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T20|1500 metres \u2013 T20]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|{{nowrap|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]}}|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] |[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] |[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metres|800m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] |[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1500m T20]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142''' ({{nee}} '''Bieganowska''' born 1 September 1981) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Poland]] competing mainly in category [[T20 (classification)|T20]] sprint and middle distance events.<ref name=\"IPC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=918822|title=Niewiedzia\u0142, Barbara|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> She is a two time Paralympic gold medalist in the [[800m]] (2000) and [[1,500 metres]] (2012) races and has won four World Athletic titles.\n\n==Personal history==\nNiewiedzia\u0142 was born Barbara Bieganowska in [[Nysa, Poland]] in 1981.<ref name=\"IPC\"/> She has two daughters.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\n==Athletics career==\nNiewiedzia\u0142 first came to note as an athlete when in 1999 she set a world record mark of 57.48 in the [[400 metres]] at a meet in Seville. She followed this with a gold medal in the [[800 metres]] at the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]] in Sydney, beating her team-mate and long-time rival [[Arleta Meloch]] into second place. After Sydney Niewidzial's career as an athlete was halted due to her classification being suspended by the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC) following the [[Cheating at the Paralympic Games|cheating scandal]] at the 2000 Games.\n\nIn 2009, the IPC decided to reinstate athletes with intellectual disabilities in readiness for the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in London. Niewiedzia\u0142's return to major international athletics came when she was selected for the Poland team at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Christchurch]]. There she competed in the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500 metres]] race, coming second to Meloch. Niewidzial followed this with a gold medal in the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500 metres]] at the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships]] in Stadskanaal before winning her second Paralympic gold in the same event in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/barbara-Niewiedzia\u0142|title=Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142|work=paralympic.org|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nNiewiedzia\u0142 had planned to retire after the London Paralympics, but the experience of competing in front of a cheering capacity crowd that the 2012 Games provided changed her decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/my-best-and-worst-moments-poland-s-barbara-Niewiedzia\u0142|title=My best and worst moments: Poland\u2019s Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142|work=paralympic.org|accessdate=23 July 2016|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>  Further success followed at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Lyon where she took gold in her favoured 1,500m. She furthered this success two years later at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships in Doha]], taking three gold medals in the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m]], [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metres|800m]] and the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m]] races.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\nIn the build up to the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]], Niewiedzia\u0142 travelled to Italy to take part in the [[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships]] in Grosseto. She won both of her races to take the 400m and 1,500m titles.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=barbara-bieganowska|name=Barbara Bieganowska|old_id=918822}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Niewiedzia\u0142, Barbara}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Poland]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Poland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Polish female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Polish female sprinters]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:People from Nysa, Poland]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Competitors in athletics with an intellectual disability]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Polish Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n| name = Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142\n| image = Barbara Niewiedzial - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Niewiedzia\u0142 at the 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships in Lyon.\n| nationality =Polish\n| sport = [[track and field]]\n| event  = [[400m]]<br/>[[800m]]<br/>[[1500m]]\n| club = MGOKSiR Korfantow\n| collegeteam = \n| coach = Mariusz Zabinski (club)<br/>Zbigniew Lewkowicz (national)\n| birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1981|09|01|df=y}}\n| disability_class = [[T20 (classification)|T20]]\n| disability= Intellectual impairment\n| birth_place = [[Nysa, Poland]]\n| residence = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| weight = \n|website = \n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|3|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|5|1|0\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|3|0|0\n}}\n{{MedalSport | [[Paralympic athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry|{{POL}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2000 Summer Paralympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Paralympics|800 metres \u2013 T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T20|1500 metres \u2013 T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]] | [[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres T20|1500 metres \u2013 T20]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|{{nowrap|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]}}|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] |[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] |[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metres|800m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]] |[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships|2017 London]]|[[2017 World Para Athletics Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1500m T20]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m - T20]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500m - T20]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142''' ({{nee}} '''Bieganowska''' born 1 September 1981) is a [[Paralympian]] [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Poland]] competing mainly in category [[T20 (classification)|T20]] sprint and middle distance events.<ref name=\"IPC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=918822|title=Niewiedzia\u0142, Barbara|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> She is a two time Paralympic gold medalist in the [[800m]] (2000) and [[1,500 metres]] (2012) races and has won four World Athletic titles.\n\n==Personal history==\nNiewiedzia\u0142 was born Barbara Bieganowska in [[Nysa, Poland]] in 1981.<ref name=\"IPC\"/> She has two daughters.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\n==Athletics career==\nNiewiedzia\u0142 first came to note as an athlete when in 1999 she set a world record mark of 57.48 in the [[400 metres]] at a meet in Seville. She followed this with a gold medal in the [[800 metres]] at the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]] in Sydney, beating her team-mate and long-time rival [[Arleta Meloch]] into second place. After Sydney Niewidzial's career as an athlete was halted due to her classification being suspended by the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC) following the [[Cheating at the Paralympic Games|cheating scandal]] at the 2000 Games.\n\nIn 2009, the IPC decided to reinstate athletes with intellectual disabilities in readiness for the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in London. Niewiedzia\u0142's return to major international athletics came when she was selected for the Poland team at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Christchurch]]. There she competed in the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1,500 metres]] race, coming second to Meloch. Niewidzial followed this with a gold medal in the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500 metres]] at the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships]] in Stadskanaal before winning her second Paralympic gold in the same event in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/barbara-Niewiedzia\u0142|title=Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142|work=paralympic.org|accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nNiewiedzia\u0142 had planned to retire after the London Paralympics, but the experience of competing in front of a cheering capacity crowd that the 2012 Games provided changed her decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/news/my-best-and-worst-moments-poland-s-barbara-Niewiedzia\u0142|title=My best and worst moments: Poland\u2019s Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142|work=paralympic.org|accessdate=23 July 2016|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>  Further success followed at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Lyon where she took gold in her favoured 1,500m. She furthered this success two years later at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships in Doha]], taking three gold medals in the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 400 metres|400m]], [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 800 metres|800m]] and the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 1,500 metres|1,500m]] races.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\nIn the build up to the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]], Niewiedzia\u0142 travelled to Italy to take part in the [[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships]] in Grosseto. She won both of her races to take the 400m and 1,500m titles.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/search.php?sport=all&games=all&medal=all&npc=all&gender=all&name=Niewiedzia\u0142&fname=Barbara Barbara Niewiedzia\u0142 at the International Paralympic Committee]{{dead link|date=July 2017}}\n* {{IPC athlete|918822}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Niewiedzia\u0142, Barbara}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Poland]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Poland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Polish female middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Polish female sprinters]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:People from Nysa, Poland]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Competitors in athletics with an intellectual disability]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Niewiedzia%C5%82"}
{"title_page": "Billy Konstantinidis", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Vasilis Konstantinidis\n| fullname    = Vasilios Konstantinidis\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1986|04|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| height      = {{convert|1.91|m|abbr=on}}\n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]]\n| clubnumber  =\n| years1 = 2000\u20132004 | caps1 = ?  | goals1 = 3  | clubs1 = [[Richmond SC|East Richmond]]\n| years2 = 2004\u20132006 | caps2 = 2  | goals2 = 0  | clubs2 = [[Veria F.C.|Veria]]\n| years3 = 2007\u20132007 | caps3 = 9  | goals3 = 0  | clubs3 = [[Nafpaktiakos Asteras F.C.|Nafpaktiakos Asteras]]\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008 | caps4 = 11 | goals4 = 0  | clubs4 = [[Lamia F.C.|Lamia]]\n| years5 = 2008\u20132010 | caps5 = 38 | goals5 = 2  | clubs5 = [[Niki Volos F.C.|Niki Volos]]\n| years6 = 2010\u20132011 | caps6 = 32 | goals6 = 1  | clubs6 = [[Pierikos F.C.|Pierikos]]\n| years7 = 2012\u20132013 | caps7 = 17 | goals7 = 7  | clubs7 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]]\n| years8 = 2013      | caps8 = 19 | goals8 = 1  | clubs8 = [[Ethnikos Gazoros F.C.|Ethnikos Gazoros]]\n| years9 = 2013\u20132014 | caps9 = 27 | goals9 = 14 | clubs9 = [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]]\n| years10= 2014      | caps10= 15 | goals10 =10 | clubs10= [[Doxa Drama F.C.|Doxa Drama]]\n| years11= 2015\u20132016 | caps11= 9  | goals11= 2  | clubs11= [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]]\n| years12= 2016\u20132017 | caps12= 4  | goals12= 0  | clubs12= [[Veria F.C.|Veria]]\n| years13= 2017      | caps13= 0  | goals13= 0  | clubs13= [[Ventforet Kofu]]\n| years14= 2018\u20132019 | caps14= 7  | goals14= 0  | clubs14= [[P.A.S.A. Irodotos F.C.|Irodotos]]\n| years15= 2019\u2013     | caps15= 0  | goals15= 0  | clubs15= [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]]\n}}\n\n'''Billy Konstantinidis''', also known as '''Vasilis Konstantinidis''' ({{lang-el|\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2}}, born 21 April 1986) is a [[Greeks|Greek]]-[[Australia]]n [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL Victoria]] club [[South Melbourne FC]].\n\n==Career==\nHe signed for Aris in January 2015 making his debut and scoring against Aris Akropotamos F.C.scoring in the 88th minute. He scored his second goal a 90th-minute winner against [[AO Kavala|Kavala]] in only his 3rd game and 2nd game at [[Kleanthis Vikelidis]] stadium. Konstandinidis plays friendly games for [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] every year. Konstandinidis has been subject of a league interest from the [[Central Coast Mariners]] [[Adelaide United]] and [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] but a move never materialized.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/208754,billys-aussie-heart.aspx | title = Billy Konstantinidis | publisher = au.fourfourtwo.com | accessdate = 4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/billy-konstantinidis/ | title = Billy Konstantinidis | publisher = worldfootball.net | accessdate = 4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://int.soccerway.com/players/vasilis-konstantinidis/155256/ | title = Billy Konstantinidis | publisher = soccerway.com | accessdate = 4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to Veria in September 2, 2016.<ref>[http://veriafc.gr/index.php/2012-10-10-16-37-41/1027-podosfairistis-tis-verias-o-konstantinidis \u03a0\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03ad\u03c1\u03bf\u03b9\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2]</ref> On 15 September 2017, he signed a contract with Japanese club [[Ventforet Kofu]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sport24.gr/football/EllinesExoterikou/kwnstantinidhs-to-ellhniko-podosfairo-dokimazei-tis-antoxes-soy.4848845.html | title = \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2: \"\u03a4\u03bf \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c0\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf \u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03b9\u03bc\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c7\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c3\u03bf\u03c5!\" | publisher = www.sport24.gr | accessdate = 16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Konstantinidis returned to Australia, signing on for the 2019 [[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL Victoria]] season with [[South Melbourne FC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smfc.com.au/south-sign-centre-forward-billy-konstantinidis-on-deadline-day/|title=South sign centre forward Billy Konstantinidis on deadline day|last=Kouroumalis|first=George|website=smfc.com.au}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{J.League player}}\n* {{Soccerway}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140407013946/http://myplayer.gr/index.php?option=com_myplayer_players&view=player&player=445 Myplayer.gr Profile]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Konstantinidis, Billy}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Veria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Lamia 1964 players]]\n[[Category:Niki Volou FC players]]\n[[Category:Pierikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panserraikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:P.A.S.A. Irodotos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:National Premier Leagues players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Vasilis Konstantinidis\n| fullname    = Vasilios Konstantinidis\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1986|04|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| height      = {{convert|1.91|m|abbr=on}}\n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]]\n| clubnumber  =\n| years1 = 2000\u20132004 | caps1 = ?  | goals1 = 3  | clubs1 = [[Richmond SC|East Richmond]]\n| years2 = 2004\u20132006 | caps2 = 2  | goals2 = 0  | clubs2 = [[Veria F.C.|Veria]]\n| years3 = 2007\u20132007 | caps3 = 9  | goals3 = 0  | clubs3 = [[Nafpaktiakos Asteras F.C.|Nafpaktiakos Asteras]]\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008 | caps4 = 11 | goals4 = 0  | clubs4 = [[Lamia F.C.|Lamia]]\n| years5 = 2008\u20132010 | caps5 = 38 | goals5 = 2  | clubs5 = [[Niki Volos F.C.|Niki Volos]]\n| years6 = 2010\u20132011 | caps6 = 32 | goals6 = 1  | clubs6 = [[Pierikos F.C.|Pierikos]]\n| years7 = 2012\u20132013 | caps7 = 17 | goals7 = 7  | clubs7 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]]\n| years8 = 2013      | caps8 = 19 | goals8 = 1  | clubs8 = [[Ethnikos Gazoros F.C.|Ethnikos Gazoros]]\n| years9 = 2013\u20132014 | caps9 = 27 | goals9 = 14 | clubs9 = [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]]\n| years10= 2014      | caps10= 15 | goals10 =10 | clubs10= [[Doxa Drama F.C.|Doxa Drama]]\n| years11= 2015\u20132016 | caps11= 9  | goals11= 2  | clubs11= [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]]\n| years12= 2016\u20132017 | caps12= 4  | goals12= 0  | clubs12= [[Veria F.C.|Veria]]\n| years13= 2017      | caps13= 0  | goals13= 0  | clubs13= [[Ventforet Kofu]]\n| years14= 2018\u20132019 | caps14= 7  | goals14= 0  | clubs14= [[P.A.S.A. Irodotos F.C.|Irodotos]]\n| years15= 2019\u2013     | caps15= 0  | goals15= 0  | clubs15= [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]]\n}}\n\n'''Billy Konstantinidis''', also known as '''Vasilis Konstantinidis''' ({{lang-el|\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2}}, born 21 April 1986) is a [[Greeks|Greek]]-[[Australia]]n [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL Victoria]] club [[South Melbourne FC]].\n\n==Career==\nHe signed for Aris in January 2015 making his debut and scoring against Aris Akropotamos F.C.scoring in the 88th minute. He scored his second goal a 90th-minute winner against [[AO Kavala|Kavala]] in only his 3rd game and 2nd game at [[Kleanthis Vikelidis]] stadium. Konstandinidis plays friendly games for [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] every year. Konstandinidis has been subject of a league interest from the [[Central Coast Mariners]] [[Adelaide United]] and [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] but a move never materialized.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/208754,billys-aussie-heart.aspx | title = Billy Konstantinidis | publisher = au.fourfourtwo.com | accessdate = 4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/billy-konstantinidis/ | title = Billy Konstantinidis | publisher = worldfootball.net | accessdate = 4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://int.soccerway.com/players/vasilis-konstantinidis/155256/ | title = Billy Konstantinidis | publisher = soccerway.com | accessdate = 4 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to Veria in September 2, 2016.<ref>[http://veriafc.gr/index.php/2012-10-10-16-37-41/1027-podosfairistis-tis-verias-o-konstantinidis \u03a0\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03ad\u03c1\u03bf\u03b9\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2]</ref> On 15 September 2017, he signed a contract with Japanese club [[Ventforet Kofu]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sport24.gr/football/EllinesExoterikou/kwnstantinidhs-to-ellhniko-podosfairo-dokimazei-tis-antoxes-soy.4848845.html | title = \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2: \"\u03a4\u03bf \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c0\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf \u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03b9\u03bc\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c7\u03ad\u03c2 \u03c3\u03bf\u03c5!\" | publisher = www.sport24.gr | accessdate = 16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Konstantinidis returned to Australia, signing on for the 2019 [[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL Victoria]] season with [[South Melbourne FC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smfc.com.au/south-sign-centre-forward-billy-konstantinidis-on-deadline-day/|title=South sign centre forward Billy Konstantinidis on deadline day|last=Kouroumalis|first=George|website=smfc.com.au}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{J.League player}}\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=155256 Scoresway.com Profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140407013946/http://myplayer.gr/index.php?option=com_myplayer_players&view=player&player=445 Myplayer.gr Profile]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Konstantinidis, Billy}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Veria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Lamia 1964 players]]\n[[Category:Niki Volou FC players]]\n[[Category:Pierikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panserraikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:P.A.S.A. Irodotos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:National Premier Leagues players]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Konstantinidis"}
{"title_page": "Ross County F.C. Records and Statistics", "text_new": "[[Ross County F.C.|Ross County Football Club]] are a Scottish professional [[association football]] club based in [[Dingwall]]. Ross County joined the [[Highland Football League]] in 1929, and then were one of two clubs voted into the [[Scottish Professional Football League]] System in 1994.\n\nThe club's record appearance maker is [[Michael Gardyne]], who has made Over 400 appearances through four spells at the club. Gardyne is also the club's record goalscorer, scoring over 70 goals in major competitions during his time at Ross County.\n\nThis list encompasses the major honours won by Ross County, records set by the club, their managers and their players.  The player records section includes details of the club's leading goalscorers and those who have made most appearances in first-team competitions. It also records notable achievements by Ross County players on the international stage, and the highest transfer fees paid and received by the club. Attendance records are also included in the list.\n\n==Honours==\n===League===\n* '''[[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]]/[[Scottish Championship|Championship]] (second tier)'''\n** '''Winners''' (2): [[2011\u201312 Scottish First Division|2011\u201312]], [[2018\u201319 Scottish Championship|2018\u201319]]\n* '''[[Scottish Football League Second Division|Second Division]] (third tier)'''\n** '''Winners''' (1): [[2007\u201308 Scottish Second Division|2007\u201308]]\n* '''[[Scottish Football League Third Division|Third Division]] (fourth tier)'''\n** '''Winners''' (1): [[1998\u201399 in Scottish football|1998\u201399]]\n* '''[[Highland Football League]]'''\n** '''Winners''' (3): 1966\u201367, [[1990\u201391 Highland Football League|1990\u201391]], [[1991\u201392 Highland Football League|1991\u201392]]\n** ''Runners-up (2)'': 1967\u201368, 1972\u201373\n* '''[[North Caledonian Football League]]'''\n** '''Winners''' (2): 1965\u201366, 1996\u201397\n\n===Cup===\n* '''[[Scottish Cup]]'''\n** ''Runners-up (1)'': [[2010 Scottish Cup Final|2009\u201310]]\n* '''[[Scottish League Cup]]:'''\n** '''Winners''' (1): [[2015\u201316 Scottish League Cup|2015\u201316]]\n* '''[[Scottish Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners''' (3): [[2006\u201307 Scottish Challenge Cup|2006\u201307]], [[2010\u201311 Scottish Challenge Cup|2010\u201311]], [[2018\u201319 Scottish Challenge Cup|2018\u201319]]\n** ''Runners-up (2)'': [[2004 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|2004\u201305]], [[2008 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|2008\u201309]]\n* '''[[Scottish Qualifying Cup|Qualifying Cup (North)]]'''\n** '''Winners''' (1): [[1993\u201394 Scottish Cup|1993\u201394]]\n** ''Runners-up (5)'': [[1933\u201334 Scottish Cup|1933\u201334]], [[1965\u201366 Scottish Cup|1965\u201366]], [[1969\u201370 Scottish Cup|1969\u201370]], [[1972\u201373 Scottish Cup|1972\u201373]], [[1973\u201374 Scottish Cup|1973\u201374]]\n* '''[[North of Scotland Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners''' (6): 1929\u201330, 1969\u201370, 1971\u201372, 1991\u201392, 2006\u201307, 2018\u201319\n* '''[[Highland League Cup]]'''\n**'''Winners''' (4): 1949\u201350, 1968\u201369, 1978\u201379, 1991\u201392\n\n===Youth===\n* '''[[SPFL Development League]] (Under-20)'''\n** '''Winners''' (1): [[2016\u201317 SPFL Development League|2016\u201317]]\n\n==Player records==\n===Individual Records===\n* '''Most Appearance Holder''': [[Michael Gardyne]] (409)\n* '''Record Goalscorer''': [[Michael Gardyne]] (71)\n* '''Most Goals in a season (all competitions)''': [[Andrew Barrowman]] (29)\n* '''Most Goals in a season (league)''': [[Andrew Barrowman]] (24)\n*'''Most Clean Sheets''': [[Nicky Walker]] (54)\n*'''Most Hat-Tricks''': [[Liam Boyce]] (5)\n\n===Most appearances===\n''As of 24 February 2020 (competitive matches only):''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Name\n! Career\n! Apps\n! Goals\n|-\n| 1\n| {{Flagicon|SCO}} '''[[Michael Gardyne]]'''\n| 2006\u20132007, 2008\u20132012, 2014\u2013201